data.title: Family party
data.text: Absolutely wonderful service for our large party. And great food and margs. Highly recommend this restaurant

data.title: Great Dining Experience
data.text: I love the outdoor seating.  Their mole sauce is simply wonderful.  Service was excellent.  A truly enjoyable dining experience.

data.title: Great place for Mexican food
data.text: Really enjoyed some very tasty enchiladas! Went here with a friend who also enjoyed hers. It was raining but I imagine that on a nice day the seating outside would have been perfect!

data.title: Lots of Good Food!
data.text: Quiet when we were there.  Good bar.  The food was really good.  I would not call it authenticate Mexican food nor would I call it Tex-Mex.  It is original!  The wait staff was very attentive.  Helpful in describing and in recommending food.  We were comfortable sitting and talking and eating - very relaxing atmosphere.  I had the burrito - and could not eat it all.  Good salsa.  The queso was different and quite tasty!

data.title: They have espresso!
data.text: At last a restaurant in California that has an espresso machine! Joking aside it was OK but nothing special the metal chairs were not comfortable. They served a huge bowl of Mexican chips with 3 hot dips, it was like chewing cardboard so we did not bother with them. I had a 100 year old recipe for chicken with black beans and rice. I was OK, all in all an average sort of place. I don't think we will bother with Mexican food again

data.title: Mexican Well Done
data.text: A great place with a large patio for outside dining on a warm evening that allows the dinner to take in the Main Street scene while enjoying the rich and flavorful meals served. The recipes are very good and some are family recipes that have been passed down for over a hundred years! The food is very good and the service attentive, but somewhat mechanical. Worth a visit.

data.title: Delicious Food and Cute Setting!
data.text: We were roaming around downtown Pleasanton and saw the Blue Agave Club.  The outdoor seating looked so cute and I had read good reviews.  I ordered the Enchiladas del Mar (one shrimp and one crab enchilada in a creamy seafood sauce) and my husband ordered the surf and turf burrito.  We had ordered guacamole as an appetizer but it never came...fine with us...it saved us $12. :) Both dishes were delicious. The burrito came with chimichurri fries...amazing! Overall, the food is good, the service is decent, and I would eat here again.

data.title: Excellent Food, Service and Atmosphere
data.text: My wife and I were on vacation in California and we thoroughly enjoyed our stop at the Blue Agave Club. Downtown Pleasanton has done a nice job of creating a nice environment with some great little restaurants. We enjoyed our experience, food was good (Mahi Mahi Ceviche was awesome), loved eating outside. Very well done.

data.title: Some hits, some misses, overall a nice experience; 3.5 stars if I could
data.text:
My wife and were trying to get away from the chilly weather near San Francisco Bay and so drove inland to stroll around charming Pleasanton and have lunch. Based on other TripAdvisor reviews, we chose to visit Blue Agave Club, and give it a try. 

We thought that the service was excellent. We received a complementary basket of housemade chips with three salsas, and iced water. Water glasses were filled regularly, and an offer of a chip refill was made before we had run out. When we were both done with lunch, plates were cleared promptly. You felt well taken care of.

The outdoor patio is a very pleasant place to eat. I can imagine that on a warm evening, with the decorative lights on, that it becomes an even more pleasant place to dine. Table separation is adequate. Music is played at a volume that helps mask the sound of passing cars on Main Street, but does not interfere with conversation at the table. If I were out in Pleasanton on a warm summer or fall night I would definitely check it out. 

We ordered two of the regional plates. My wife opted for the chicken mole, and I had the carnitas plate. Both came with rice, mine came with black beans and various sides (onions, lettuce, sour cream, tomato, and a guacamole puree). You had your choice of corn or flour tortillas, which came warmed in a basket. The portions of pork and chicken were substantial. My wife liked the mole itself; she said it had good flavor. I similarly liked the shredded pork; the fat was fully rendered, and it had good flavor. We both felt that the meats were a bit dried out. For the pork there is the issue of fully rendering the fat, but once the fat is rendered, even a pork shoulder will eventually dry out. What was billed as having been cooked for 24 hours might actually have been a bit better if it had only been cooked a bit less. I did not consider this a terribly serious flaw, but I prefer pork a little moister and more unctuous. The matter of chicken is a bit different. Breast meat tends to be less fatty and thus dries out much more easily. If there had been more mole, than perhaps it would not have been as much of an issue, but just looking at the cut surfaces of the chicken, there was no juice flowing. It even looked dry across the table. So that dish could have been better, but we were not willing to send it back or have the item recooked. Perhaps we got unlucky on that choice. 

Overall, I like the restaurant. Again, the service was attentive and professional. The seating area is pleasant, and would have been even more pleasant had we dined on a slightly warmer day. I was happy to see that there were salt and pepper shakers on the tables. I did not need either for the dishes we ordered, but I dislike restaurants that now make you ask for salt and pepper. I worry that soon I will need to bring my own cutlery or ask for a fork. The food was good to very good. There was no dish that I would drive 35 miles each way to sample again, and because of the drive I would be quite restrained in sampling tequilas. I enjoyed the salsa medley, but we are fortunate to have a nearby restaurant with roughly twenty salsas in their salsa bar. I suspect that I can find good mole more locally as well. The value was average to good. Our lunch tab for two with the tip but without any drinks came to around $50. So if you are staying in or near Pleasanton, and want a Mexican meal with excellent service in pleasant surroundings, I will certainly recommend Blue Agave Club. If I could walk to a hotel, I might really enjoy the tequila selection. For us, I don’t think we would drive all the way to Pleasanton just to dine there. That should not be interpreted as a slight, it is just a matter of having many wonderful options substantially closer to home that avoid a 50-minute drive each way even when traffic is light.

data.title: Not your regular tacos and nachos mexican restaurant
data.text: I love Mexican food but this place has more than the regular burritos and tacos. It is like a fine dining mexican restaurant. They have a variety of entrees with different moles. Their tortilla soup was superb as well. It is nice to dine outside at sundown.

data.title: Excellent food and Margaritas!
data.text: This is a higher-end Mexican restaurant.  I particularly like their lunch menu and their margarita's are delicious, especially the La Lorna (not sure of spelling).   They also have a fabulous back patio for parties.  For a regular lunch or dinner, I recommend sitting outside in front.

data.title: Great location
data.text: On Main St. large outdoor dining and cozy front porch dining in this old victorian style house. Mexican cuisine. Average food and very pricey for that type of cuisine.

data.title: Tequila central
data.text: I have come to depend on the Blue Agave Club as a place to meet clients for a business lunch. This is especially appropriate for my clients who fancy themselves tequila aficionados. It never fails to impress even the most experienced and well-traveled fans of this plant. The food is good, but almost an after thought. I've had guests spend 15 minutes on the tequila offerings and when the server came to take our orders were chagrined that they had not even looked at the food options. It's easily remedied because the servers seem to have a sense of what people want to eat and food orders get done quickly.

data.title: Blue Agave Club Experience
data.text: Blue Agave Club is one of the more popular eateries in downtown Pleasanton's Main Street, boasting an impressive list of premium tequilas.  The dining room and small bar are located in an old farm house tricked out with Mexican decorations and furniture but the highlight is the outdoor seating found in front of the restaurant.  The menu features a healthier version of the traditional Mexican dishes with no lard as well as vegetarian rice and beans.  Be aware that there is no air conditioning so probably not the best choice for hot days and nights.

data.title: Good Mexican Food
data.text: Great place to have a family get together with lots of room to eat outside their street patio and enjoy the street business

data.title: Yummy Mexican food
data.text:
Good Mexican food fast service as well.
The place is a little pricey. Mixed drinks are pretty good but pricey.
Inside dining area can be a little cramped

data.title: Great drinks outside
data.text:
We went for drinks and appetizers outside. Lively vibe with a blend of couples, families and work families. The tequila selection is impressive, to say the least. Better do some research beforehand! Food was good, not great. I don't think our server spoke much English as he didn't make any small talk beyond "good evening". 

We thought it odd to make a point of mentioning a 3% health care surcharge. Maybe a political statement? Resort fee? Also, despite dire warnings about not serving water to the table unless requested, my water glass was never more than half empty. 

So, I would go again, but wouldn't go out of my way to eat there.

data.title: Lunch
data.text: It was okay .... But did not meet the hype I've heard about.  It really did not leave me with a feeling to try them again .....

data.title: A treat
data.text: Excellent food and drink, live music, outdoor seating...wish it wasn't expensive, but has never failed to be a treat. Food that I've never had at a "Mexican" restaurant!!

data.title: Work and some recreation
data.text:
We were at Pleasanton for work but at night we like to sample the restaurants around. One happy place we saw was Blue Agave Club right in the heart of downtown Pleasanton. Since the fair was going on at that time, you just cant help but jive with the festive air around. We found this really happy and lively setting that Blue Agave have and we were instantly drawn to the atmosphere. The place was booked. We came and were told that we have to wait for awhile but managed to sit us in less than 10 minute wait. The waiters/ staff were friendly and the chips and salsa were exceptional. They put 3 types of salsa and we loved them all. We were also satisfied with the main dish we ordered. 
Bottomline, we will definitely come back to try other dishes
